The 2014–15 season was [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s 23rd season in the [[Premier League]], and their 40th consecutive season in the top-flight of [[Football in England|English football]].

United began the season on 16 August 2014, with the opening game of their [[Premier League]] campaign. They also competed in two [[Football in England#Cup competitions|domestic cups]], the [[2014–15 FA Cup|FA Cup]] and the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]. This was the first season since [[1989–90 Manchester United F.C. season|1989–90]] that Manchester United did not compete in any [[UEFA competitions|European competition]].

==Background==
United finished seventh<ref name="vangaal">{{cite news |title=Manchester United: Louis van Gaal confirmed as new manager |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27243233 |work=BBC Sport |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=19 May 2014 }}</ref> in the [[Premier League]] [[2013–14 Premier League|last season]] so did not participate in the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the first time since the [[1995–96 UEFA Champions League|1995–96 campaign]]<ref name="vangaal"/> and were not in any European competition for the first time in 25 years.<ref name="vangaal"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Van Gaal neuer Coach bei Manchester United |url=http://sport.oe24.at/fussball/Van-Gaal-neuer-Coach-bei-Manchester-United/143924410 |newspaper=Österreich |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=19 May 2014 |language=German }}</ref> [[Louis van Gaal]] was announced as the new manager on 19 May 2014 after the sacking of [[David Moyes]] in April.<ref name="vangaal"/> He appointed [[Ryan Giggs]], who retired from playing,<ref>{{cite news |first=Jamie |last=Jackson |title=Ryan Giggs retires from playing after taking Manchester United No2 job |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/19/ryan-giggs-manchester-united-assistant |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=19 May 2014 }}</ref> as assistant manager, [[Marcel Bout]] as assistant coach, specialising in oppositional scouting, and [[Frans Hoek]] as goalkeeping coach.<ref name="vangaal"/> [[Rio Ferdinand]],<ref name="Ferdinand"/> [[Nemanja Vidić]]<ref name="Vidić"/> and [[Patrice Evra]]<ref name="Evra"/> left the club. United completed their first signing of the season on 26 June 2014 with the acquisition of [[Ander Herrera]] from [[Athletic Bilbao]] for £29&nbsp;million,<ref name="herrera">{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Stone |title=Ander Herrera: Man Utd confirm deal for Athletic Bilbao midfielder |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27993874 |work=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref> and followed this up the following day with [[Luke Shaw]] from [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref name="shaw">{{cite news |title=Luke Shaw: Man Utd sign Southampton defender for £27M |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28048866 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref> Following the departures of Vidić and Evra, [[Wayne Rooney]] and [[Darren Fletcher]] were named as captain and vice-captain respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/12/wayne-rooney-manchester-united-captain-louis-van-gaal|title=Wayne Rooney named Manchester United’s club captain by Louis van Gaal|first=Jamie|last=Jackson|date=12 August 2014|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>

==Pre-season and friendlies==
Manchester United preceded their 2014–15 campaign with a tour of the United States. They played [[LA Galaxy]] in the Chevrolet Cup on 23 July, and also participated in the [[2014 International Champions Cup]] from 26 July to 2 August, playing against [[A.S. Roma|Roma]], [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] and [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the group stage. The match against Real Madrid on 2 August set a US attendance record of 109,318.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/03/real-madrid-manchester-united-pre-season-friendly-match-report|title=Real Madrid 1-3 Manchester United - Pre-season friendly match report|first=Jamie Jackson at Michigan|last=Stadium|date=3 August 2014|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Having beaten Roma and Real Madrid in normal time, and Internazionale on penalties to win their group, they qualified for the final against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 4 August. After going behind to a [[Steven Gerrard]] penalty in the first half, United rallied in the second with goals from Wayne Rooney, [[Juan Mata]] and [[Jesse Lingard]] to win 3–1. Upon their return to England, the team played against [[Valencia C.F.|Valencia]] on 12 August in what was Louis van Gaal's first home match as Manchester United manager.

