==Premier League==
{{main|2014–15 Premier League}}
The fixtures for the 2014–15 league season were announced on 18 June 2014. Manchester United opened their Premier League campaign at home to [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on 16 August 2014, and their last game of the season was away to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on 24 May 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fixtures 2014/15: OT start |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2014/Jun/manchester-united-premier-league-fixtures-2014-15-season.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=18 June 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2014 }}</ref> The season started off on the wrong foot for Manchester United, losing 2–1 at home to [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], marking Swansea's first league win at Old Trafford in club history and the ''Red Devils''' first home loss in a season opener since [[1972–73 Manchester United F.C. season|1972]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28718345 |title=Man Utd 1–2 Swansea |work=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2014 |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> [[Juan Mata]] gave United the lead away at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] but [[Jack Rodwell]] equalised on his debut, meaning the match finished as a draw, before United ended August with a laboured 0–0 draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], despite [[Ángel Di María]] making his debut for the ''Red Devils''.

The draw was followed up with United's first win of the season, a 4–0 thumping of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. However, the following week, 2–0 and 3–1 leads were blown as the ''Red Devils'' suffered a remarkable 5–3 defeat away to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. September concluded with a nervy 2–1 home win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] despite captain Wayne Rooney's sending-off for a reckless kick at the legs of [[Stewart Downing]].

The next fixture, without club captain Rooney, was a morale-boosting 2–1 home victory over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], who had achieved the league double over United the previous season. [[Radamel Falcao]] netted the winner with his first goal for United. The next two matches were last-minute draws against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and league leaders [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], respectively.

A United side which was severely depleted in defence then narrowly lost to city rivals [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 2 November, with [[Sergio Agüero]]'s goal separating the teams at the [[Etihad Stadium (Manchester)|Etihad Stadium]]. The next match, a 1–0 victory over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] courtesy of a Juan Mata strike, ignited a six-match winning run that took United to third place in the table. Although United recorded wins over Premier League giants [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and in-form [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], they were greatly indebted to Spanish goalkeeper [[David de Gea]], who made many game-saving stops. United then drew away to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], with new signing Falcao scoring his second goal for the club. The Boxing Day clash against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]] at Old Trafford was a 3–1 win, with Wayne Rooney scoring twice and assisting a goal for [[Robin van Persie]].

The next game, only two days later, was a goalless draw away to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. The result was the same against Stoke on New Year's Day, with Falcao's goal unable to win the game in a 1–1 draw. The following match, United ended their unbeaten streak with a home defeat to Southampton — the first time the Saints had won at Old Trafford in 27 years. Next week, United secured a 2–0 win against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] at [[Loftus Road]], with [[Marouane Fellaini]] and [[James Wilson (footballer, born 1995)|James Wilson]] scoring. On 31 January United beat Leicester City 3–1 at Old Trafford with goals from Van Persie and Falcao, thus gaining a measure of revenge for their early-season mauling at the [[King Power Stadium]].

United had to claw back a 1–1 draw at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]] against West Ham on February 8 thanks to an equaliser in stoppage time from [[Daley Blind]]. After this, United won 3–1 against Burnley at Old Trafford, with two goals in the first half from substitute [[Chris Smalling]], and a late penalty from Van Persie, although the ''Red Devils''' performance was far from their best.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Hibbs |title=Smalling: We let ourselves down |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Feb/Chris-Smalling-pleased-to-beat-Burnley-but-says-the-players-let-themselves-down.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=11 February 2015 |accessdate=13 February 2015 }}</ref> On 21 February, United suffered their first away defeat since November as Swansea did the double on the ''Red Devils'' for the first time in their history, winning 2–1, resulting in United dropping to fourth place.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31466678 |title=Swansea 2 – 1 Man Utd |work=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2015 |accessdate=22 February 2015 |first=Dafydd |last=Pritchard}}</ref> United got back to winning ways with a 2–0 home victory over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31562858 |title=Manchester United 2–0 Sunderland |work=BBC Sport |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> which was followed by a 1–0 away victory against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 4 March, the winner coming from [[Ashley Young]] after a late defensive error from Newcastle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31617021 |title=Newcastle United 0–1 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>

The following fixture, United secured a storming 3–0 home victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] to boost their chances of a top four finish.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31785852 |title=Manchester United 3–0 Tottenham Hotspur |work=BBC Sport |date=15 March 2015 |accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref> Their next game was against arch-rivals [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]]. United won the match courtesy of a brace from Juan Mata to secure the double over their rivals.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31893202 |title=Liverpool 1–2 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=22 March 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>

After the international break, United's next opponents were league strugglers [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] at Old Trafford on 4 April 2015. United won the match 3–1 with a brace from [[Ander Herrera]] and a goal from [[Wayne Rooney]] to move up to third in the Premier League table.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32097849 |title=Manchester United 3–1 Aston Villa |work=BBC Sport |first=Michael |last=Emons |date=4 April 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> On 12 April 2015, United claimed their first [[Manchester derby]] win since 2012 over neighbours [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] – a stunning 4–2 victory with goals from Young, Fellaini, Mata, and Smalling.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32187754 |title=Manchester United 4–2 Manchester City |work=BBC Sport |first=Phil |last=McNulty |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> United failed to extend their winning run, and suffered their first defeat in six games to league leaders [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32262278 |title=Chelsea 1–0 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=18 April 2015 |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> United then suffered their second straight defeat the following week, in a 3–0 loss to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. This meant the ''Red Devils'' had failed to win at [[Goodison Park]] for the third season running.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32371018 |title=Everton 3–0 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=26 April 2015 |accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>

On 2 May 2015, Manchester United failed to bounce back as they suffered a 1–0 home defeat to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. It was the first time since [[2000–01 Manchester United F.C. season|2001]] that United lost three consecutive matches, meaning the ''Red Devils'' remained in fourth place.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32460284 |title=Manchester United 0–1 West Bromwich Albion |work=BBC Sport |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> On 9 May 2015, United beat [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] 2–1 to end their losing run.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32561782 |title=Crystal Palace 1–2 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref> In their penultimate game of the season on 17 May, United faced [[Arsenal and Manchester United rivalry|rivals]] [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. The match ended in a 1–1 draw, ensuring the ''Red Devils'' would compete in the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] next season following a one-year absence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32679743 |title=Manchester United 1–1 Arsenal |work=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref> United's final match of the season against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] ended in a draw, relegating the Tigers, although they would have been relegated regardless of the result.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32770866 |title=Hull City 0–0 Manchester United |work=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2015 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> Manchester United ended the season in fourth place – three places, and six points higher than the previous season.

